block body
  .container-fluid
    .row.panel.panel--remitly-intro
      .default-text
        h1.text-center The Remitly pattern library
        //- p.text-center Creating a flexible but consistent cross-platform experience


    .row
      .default-text
        h2 Premise

        p As Remitly scaled its money sending operations from 3 countries to roughly a dozen, managing location-specific implementations became costly. Engineering made the decision to replace the front end with something more maintainable, which was the right opportunity to also overhaul a UI that hadn’t gotten much love in the past

        p This pattern library helped us keep a consistent execution across multiple corridors with customized experiences based on cultural and regulatory expectations, while also serving as a platform for quickly testing variations on the product.


    //- Existing brand widget
    .panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-sm-20.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-18.col-md-offset-3.shadow(style="background-color:white; padding: 80px 0; overflow: hidden;")
          .col-xs-18.col-xs-offset-3.col-lg-7.col-lg-offset-2.md-vertical-center(style="padding-bottom: 20px;")
            h4(style="color: #FF3F00; margin-bottom: 0;") Context
            h2(style="color: #173A4A; margin-top: 0;") Existing brand
            
            p The first pass at a mobile version of this app adhered closely to 
              a(href="http://www.weareairlift.com/case-study/remitly") the existing print guidlines
              | - dark backgrounds, and white text on bright reds and greens. However, it wasn’t long until the glaring UX implications led us to develop an alternate theme that would incorporate form design best practices - especially around error handling, while still feeling on-brand.
          .col-xs-18.col-xs-offset-3.col-lg-11.col-lg-offset-2
            img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_existing_brand_simple.png", style="width: 100%;")

    .row
      .default-text
        h1.text-center A living style guide from the ground up.
    .row
      .default-text(style="padding-top: 0;")
        h2 Color

        p The UI environment is demanding of colors that are less welcome in marketing materials. Yellows become browns for contrast and readability purposes. Hover states mean additional shaded / tinted versions of things. The product design color palette took the original marketing palette and filled in the gaps for performance in a broader set of environments.

    //- Desktop version
    .hidden-xs.panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-sm-20.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-18.col-md-offset-3.shadow.card
          img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_palette.png", style="width: 100%;")

    //- Mobile version
    .visible-xs.panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-xs-22.col-xs-offset-1.shadow.card
          img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_palette.png", style="width: 100%;")

    .row
      .default-text
        h2 Spacing

        p Our spacing began with an exponential scale. It felt like a great start, though we ended up missing some intermediate sizes (12px and 24px) and adding them in.

    //- Desktop version
    .hidden-xs.panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-sm-20.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-18.col-md-offset-3.shadow.card
          img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_spacing.png", style="width: 100%;")

    //- Mobile version
    .visible-xs.panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-xs-22.col-xs-offset-1.shadow.card
          img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_spacing.png", style="width: 100%;")

    .row
      .default-text
        h2 Typography

        p The goal of the type stack was to have a top end that was bold enough for marketing heros, and a bottom end that was robust enough for legal documents with multiple levels of headings. We borrowed an abstraction from bootstrap and extended the headings with two Display sizes that enhanced the h1 while keeping the h1s themselves at a sane size.

    //- Desktop version
    .hidden-xs.hidden-sm.panel.panel--remitly-pale
      .row
        .col-sm-20.col-sm-offset-2.col-md-18.col-md-offset-3.shadow.card
          img(src="/img/remitly/remitly_type.jpg", style="width: 100%;")

